section.section:
"Police officer" means:
Any uniformed law enforcement officer who is certified or under the direction of a law enforcement officer who is certified by the Department of State Police to perform an inspection authorized under this section;
Any civilian employee of the Department of State Police assigned to enforce any rule or regulation adopted under this section, but only while acting under written authorization of the Secretary of State Police;
Any civilian employee of the Maryland Transportation Authority Police who is:
Acting under the immediate direction and control of a uniformed police officer;
Acting under the written authorization of the Secretary of State Police; and
Certified by the Department of State Police to perform an inspection authorized under this section; or
Any civilian employee of a local government who is:
Acting under the immediate direction and control of a uniformed police officer;
Acting under the written authorization of the Secretary of State Police; and
Certified by the Department of State Police to perform an inspection authorized under this section.

Any rule or regulation adopted pursuant to this subsection shall:
Be formulated jointly by the Motor Vehicle Administration and the Department of State Police;
Duplicate or be consistent with the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulations contained in:
49 C.F.R., Part 385, Subparts A, C, and D ("New Entrant Safety Assurance Program");
49 C.F.R., Part 386, Subparts F and G ("Injunctions and Imminent Hazards; Penalties"); and
49 C.F.R., Parts 390 through 399 ("General Safety Requirements");
Apply to all vehicles over 10,000 pounds rated gross vehicle weight that are subject to the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulations;
Apply to vehicles over 10,000 pounds gross vehicle weight rating that are not subject to the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Regulations, if the rule or regulations adopted by the Motor Vehicle Administration specifically states that it applies to the vehicle; and
Be consistent with 49 C.F.R., Parts 40 and 382, with respect to alcohol and drug testing regulations applicable to drivers required by regulation to possess a commercial driver's license.

During normal business hours, trained personnel from the Commercial Vehicle Enforcement Division of the Department of State Police may enter the premises and inspect, review, and copy records of motor carriers subject to the regulations adopted under this section, § 22-409 of this article, or § 23-302 of this article, including:
Any record required by this section;
Driver qualification files;
Hours of service records;
Drug and alcohol testing records of drivers required to be tested under this section; and
Insurance records.
